out 1265","Caerlaverock, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Caerlaverock, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","or near Renfrewshire, Scotland ":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pearson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Per(e)</i> or <i>Piers</i> (see   Pear   and   Pierce  ) + <i>son</i>. The surname is also quite common in Ireland, where it has been established for many centuries. Compare   Peerson  .","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish (Ashkenazic) surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Peerson","meanings":["Altered form of English   Pearson   and of English or North German   Pierson  .","Americanized form of Swedish <b>Peersson</b>: patronymic from the personal name <i>Peer</i>, a variant of <i>Per</i>, vernacular shortened form of   Peter  . The surname <i>Peersson</i> is not found in Sweden anymore (compare   Persson  ).","Americanized form of Norwegian or Danish <b>Peersen</b>, a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Pear","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Dov.","English: topographic name from residence by a pear tree (Middle English <i>pere</i>, Old English <i>peru</i>, <i>pere</i>). Compare   Perry  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>pere</i>, Old French <i>per</i>, <i>peer</i> ‘peer or paragon’, also ‘companion’."]},{"name":"Pierson","meanings":["English: variant of   Pearson  .","North German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Pier</i>, a variant of <i>Peer</i>, vernacular shortened form of   Peter  . Compare   Peerson  .","History: Born in Yorkshire, England, Abraham Pierson (1609–78) was the first pastor of the settlements at Southampton, Long Island, NY; Branford, CT, and Newark, NJ. He left his library of more than 400 books, one of the most extensive in the colonies, to his son Abraham, who was one of the first trustees of Yale College."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Pearson was born about 1243, in Scotland. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Petrus de Pollock."},"et":{"about 1243–":"umbes 1243–Surnud","1230–1295":"1230–1295","1265–1304":"1265–1304","1265–1330":"1265–1330","1243–Female":"1243–Surnud","1304":"1304","1243":"1243","1265":"1265","1330":"1330","1230":"1230","5 June 1265":"5. juuni 1265","1295":"1295","about 1243":"umbes 1243","about 1265":"umbes 1265","Caerlaverock, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Caerlaverock, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","or near Renfrewshire, Scotland ":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1243–":"noin 1243–Kuollut","1230–1295":"1230–1295","1265–1304":"1265–1304","1265–1330":"1265–1330","1243–Female":"1243–Kuollut","1304":"1304","1243":"1243","1265":"1265","1330":"1330","1230":"1230","5 June 1265":"5. kesäkuuta 1265","1295":"1295","about 1243":"noin 1243","about 1265":"noin 1265","Caerlaverock, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Caerlaverock, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","or near Renfrewshire, Scotland ":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1243–":"environ 1243–Décédée","1230–1295":"1230–1295","1265–130